  "prompt": "Which type of fire extinguisher must not be used on electrical equipment?",
  "response": "Water-based fire extinguishers **must not** be used on electrical equipment. This is because water conducts electricity, which can lead to electrical shocks or further spread the fire. Instead, for electrical fires (classified as Class C fires), you should use one of the following types of fire extinguishers:\n\n1. **Carbon Dioxide (CO\u2082) Extinguishers**: These are non-conductive and effective for extinguishing electrical fires without leaving residue.\n2. **Dry Chemical Extinguishers (e.g., ABC Powder Extinguishers)**: These are versatile and can handle Class A (ordinary combustibles), B (flammable liquids), and C (electrical) fires.\n3. **Clean Agent Extinguishers**: These use halocarbon agents that are safe for electrical equipment and leave no residue.\n\n**Always ensure you're using the appropriate type of extinguisher for the specific class of fire to maximize safety and effectiveness.**\n\n**Summary:** Water-based (Class\u202fA) extinguishers should\u202fnot\u202fbe used on electrical equipment fires.",
